segments.text: The post artillery taking up the whole military wall.
As soon as the commanders were in place, if there were any individual unit announcements to be made, then either the first sergeant or the commander would make that announcement.
And you all had fallen out on military walk?
Well, we lined up out there.
Facing Sebesa?
No, we lined up facing west.
Oh, facing, oh, okay.
We lined up facing west, and when we were ready, when everything was ready, the command, the regimental commander gave a command.
had to be relayed down the way and everybody to the right place at the same time and step off at the same time.
We normally never had the band with us.
So we just marched and Sevesa fanned, the entrance to Sevesa was fanned into three entries and every
unit had its place and after about the third day every student had his place.
The normal setup was that the food, well a table was of a size you could have four
There are four students on each side and one on each end.
Totally ten.
Normally, there'd be upperclassmen on one side and possibly the ends.
Opposite then would be four freshmen.
It was the freshmen.
Now, the food was served in family style and sizable.
bowls and platters, and served by student waiters.
And it was all ready to go.
Well, it was there almost within moments after the students came in and sat down.
The job of the freshman was to see that every upperclassman at the table had his opportunity at whatever food there was.
And they took it all up, and the president didn't get any, while the waiter was to go get some more and bring that.
All that was done without any words or anything else.
And it was, you know, it worked very well.
Was there slang for the food then?
Slang names?
Oh, yeah.
Share those with us, please.
Well, bread with gun lighting.
Let me think.
Tea, coffee, tea, water, ketchup.
Well, let me back up a little bit in my way.
What I was about up to was the whole routine.
Oh, okay.
All right.
As soon as L had been in the mess hall and as soon as there had been time for everyone to be served, then on the PA system, prior to that, there had been music of the day recordings on the PA system.
But after everyone was in and ready and settled, then the
PA announcer would come on the battalion, the team's hood, and he would read off whatever orders of the day there were.
And in that day and time, it was a big deal to have a special delivery letter.
And they always had them to breakfast.
In fact, there's a guy named Graham Purcell, and they're so-called, everyone, every day.
Everybody knew him by name, you know.
And that would be the bulk of it.
I just, man, I can't remember all the names for the clues, but I didn't get them.
All right, what was your?
Of the food, you recall, what were your favorites and your unfavorites as to tastiness?
Well, to tell you the truth, I never had any trouble with any of it.
Okay.
It was all well done.
It was well cooked, well served.
The freshmen, the freshmen had to see that the upperclassmen got all they wanted.
After that, the freshmen got what was left, which is ordinarily in there.
Every place had two little quarter pounds of milk and a glass of water and a glass of milk.
And it was generally customary that once the
meal had been finished by the upperclassmen or the freshmen could do what they called a meal handing, which was to go and gather up the milk or whatever it was that they wanted.
At breakfast that was all from the cereal, but the cereal came in the little individual package boxes.
At noon also
The one big item that had its own name was kush, as dessert, which ordinarily was a pie, pies.
For ten boys, there'd be three pies, three pies on each table.
And each pie was always only cut
One slice across one way and 90 degrees in that was the other way.
Always in four pieces.
Never any different.
So there were 12 pieces for 10 people.
Well, it was there on the table.
That's what I mean.
But that way the upperclassmen could get what they want.
But until after Thanksgiving or Thanksgiving year,
Well, the freshmen never did get any kush, except what was left over after all the rest of them had left.
And, uh, the, uh, anybody that didn't get enough to eat, well, you could, after the upperclassmen were gone, well, they could go and roam, and that was called meal handling.
Uh, kush, uh,
Tell me then from, let's start it after breakfast.
Describe a typical weekday, class day.
Well.
Got up at what time?
Reveille.
Well, Reveille was at 6.15.
And the vehicle blew it up outside and
So you knew you had to get up and get your rims straightened up and get your toes on.
And those days, I don't think any of us worried about shaving.
And he was ready to go out at 5 to 7 for formation.
And we'd go, and after the meal,
In our case, we ate in Spiegel.
So there was time to go down to the post office where each of us could order them.
We had a box to share.
And then we could get back to our room.
And if we had an 8 o'clock class, we'd go and get ready until it was 8 o'clock.
or there was later, we'd go back to the room and study or mock around or whatever we were going to do.
There never was any big deal of pressure or pushing around or anything like that.
If some freshman had not done something to some of the freshmen's favor,
The only time something would happen about that would be the latter part of the morning or in the afternoon or in the evening.
The mornings generally went pretty much business like.
Now you fell out into formation for breakfast and for supper, is that right?
Oh and for lunch also.
Now, the same routine went on for breakfast and lunch.
But for dinner, we had the retreat formation.
And generally, it consisted of to the color as the flag was lowered.
And we could hear the band across the campus when we started playing.
Now, normally the band would be playing where?
Well, I don't know where they were before I got there, but all the time I was there, the band played in the center area of what at that time was known as the New Dome.
The New Dome, all right.
I guess you'd say out front of the Dome.
Okay.
And then when you all had core drills, when were they held?
And about how often?
Well, there would be a, it was not unusual, 430, like, somewhere in there, for each outfit to have their own grip.
That would be when the freshmen are lined up to how to fall in, how to.
do right and left face, how to march, what to do.
And sometimes we'd just march around until we hit them.
And where would you all normally do that?
Military wall.
Right close to the gun.
Core drill, as such,
Well, it was up to each, you know, the chain of command set up for that.
Because the Corps commander, he ran the show, then there were the Residential Commanders, then there were the Battalion Commanders, then there were the Unit Commanders.
There never was anything except everybody would fall out at x time and do less and so on, unless it was like four or a year.
I really would differentiate between that time and now.
There was a lot less pressure on any individual.
But I never did that.
We all knew that we had a certain amount of hazing to do, whether it was holding up the wall or push-ups or duck walking or knee bends.
You said that no board until after Thanksgiving.
What would a board be used for after that?
You've certainly heard of the use of a board in hazing to the hazing process with the board.
Who could use the board?
Well, of course, the seniors could do whatever they wanted to.
Juniors followed, and then...
Depending on the status of, by that I mean, the behavior, the overall well-being or well-acting of the freshman or the sophomore, it was a stair-step, you might say,
permission and nobody was to get hurt and so the procedure was the cadet, if the board was going to be applied, the word was grab a pooch and the boy would grab his
and at the same time flex the muscles in his buttocks so that he really, after a little bit, he got to where he is in pretty strong steel back there.
And as a result, after a little bit, some of the more dashing freshmen would aggravate the upperclassmen just so he'd try it again.
Because if the striking person got out of a thin band right across the center of the buttocks, why, he was called for a shit leg.
And the offended got to retaliate.
And that kind of kept things in focus.
Tell me about, and we're talking about before the war, because I'll bet things were different after the war.
Before you left for the war, tell me about some of the jokes, the pranks, the good bull that you knew about.
Were there anything that you or others did that would, for fun, that were pranks, jokes, good bulls?
Well, I got two of them that I participated in.
Let me hold off on that one.
Oh, okay.
Have you heard about the authority of the upper class and senior class and how they exercised it in 1940?
No, tell me about it, please.
Well, in the month of December 1940,
The school was hit with a massive outbreak of the flu.
And they was over at the infirmary while they had kids laying on the floor.
It was all over the place.
And they told them to stay in your room and do this.
You know, it was really a terrible epidemic.
And so a week before ordinary times,
leave for Christmas, the senior class met and said, we're going home.
And they released, they released school and everybody went home a full week early.
And that kind of gives you an idea of the way that school was run and the authority of the senior class.
There are also
But a couple things happened.
My job was a janitor in the library.
And it was in the book stacks back in the back.
I never got out on the front porch.
Parenthetically, one of the reasons I never did smoke was because out in the reading area is why the rack of the day was spitting old and dull dirt.
And that rarely got extinguished while we were there.
And I had all of that that I wanted, but I
Fortunately, I didn't have to put up with much of it, but I never cared for any smoking ever in my life.
So they could smoke in the library.
Yeah.
But the thing that attracted my attention on that job in the library was in the stacks.
Well, that's where all the trash was put.
And they had a couple of real, several real models, one of which was a tow sack.
I'd always thought a toesight might be four or five feet long.
Here's some that were ten feet long.
Or more.
And the next thing I noticed was that the library lighting had some bulbs that were about the size of a basketball.
And they had some others that were maybe down to the size of a volleyball.
Well, they burned out and so the guys that were working that part of the library took them out and they put them in the trash and the trash came out in my area.
And I began to sort of dream about what could happen to those over there next to the houses.
So I collected and collected and collected.
I had about three of those, two or three full of those big bugs.
And I got three of my roommates and a couple of other guys.
And during the final exam in the spring of 41, we went over to the library and gathered up my tow sacks and took them back.
And all the way up to the fourth floor of Mitchell,
And there was a small trap door in the shower room, but we managed to get up there and get all these sacks through there.
And, oh, about 1230 in the morning, while we stated ourselves strategically around the periphery of the roof, and then when we decided time to go, we just lulled these
They drove over the side.
They dropped four floors, boom, boom, boom, boom, boom, boom, you know, and just kept it up.
And then every two of them came from the same place, and the old business, you know, hollering, yelling, cut it out, cut it out.
They were screaming bloody murder down below, and they didn't know anything about it.
Did you get caught?
About who it was?
No.

We just kept going until we ran out of bugs and of course about the time there were several, several of them tried to send me up the scale of the wall and you know that you can cure that by just landing on close by.
So we kept that up and it
I guess we carried that on for 30, 45 minutes.
It was something else.
We waited over an hour and quietly went down one at a time.
Now, and you and the other bombers were all freshmen?
Yeah.
And then another one was the...
In the mess hall, of course, we got these little individual cereal boxes.
And this sort of a game to collect them up.
Food was hard to come by in the dorms.
We, of course, were only about 75 feet from Casey's, a confectioner there.
in the bottom of the YMCA there.
It was hardly an eating place.
You'd get a milkshake or a lot of milk there, but that's not all.
Anyway, we collected these boxes.
And we had a good bunch of them, and it got to be warm weather, and ground out time became, you know,
And my good friend from Fort Worth, he lived directly below, and he had a roommate from Dallas.
Well, over time, we had washed our socks in the lavatory in our room, and the water pipe wasn't sealed at the floor as a lot of them are in those times.
And if we slopped a little water over it,
run down the pipe and there was a joint just, I don't know, let the water run down that pipe and splatter.
It would get all over their room and so forth.
And they didn't really appreciate it.
We weren't really trying to be
Well, they got kind of contentious after a while.

So, my friend from Fort Worth, he'd stick his head out in the, in the uh, in the uh, in the uh, in the uh, in the uh, in the uh, in the uh, in the uh, in the uh, in the uh, in the uh, in the uh, in the uh,
by any time anything like that happened while we were all dried up.
But finally we decided maybe it would be a good idea to get rid of all that cereal.
So we took two wastebaskets and went into the shower and
filling up with water.
It happened that the water wasn't exactly cold.
We got a hold of some of the warm water.
But anyway, we filled up these two place passes.
And so we went down and after they'd gone to sleep down below us, well, we went down and went in and took the going out boat.
very politely lifted on the dressing.
We took the doorknob off and that's it.
And then we simultaneously, one bucket full on the upper bunk and one bucket full on the lower bunk, slammed the door and took off.
And we had to go down to the second floor and up to the fourth one, which we did.
Well, we
They came up, came in our room and felt the bottom of our feet to see if there was any dirt on them.
And we didn't find any.
So we went away, drunk and mad.
the principal character in that thing.
He didn't find it out until I made a mistake telling it at a reunion about five years ago.
Now, and the victim was a sophomore?
No, he was a freshman too.
Oh, a freshman also.
Oh, okay.
So you play, it was a good bull of one fish on another fish.
Yeah.
Let's see.
Tell me about some of the special...
teachers, advisors, who were some of the folks in your A&M years that really were special to you?
Well, number one has to be Dr. J.G.H.
Thompson.
Did he have a nickname?
Alphabet.
He later was considered to be the father of the F-16 aircraft because of
the designers and the principal, people who developed the F-16, all their students.
And one of them, my good friend and classmate, Terrence Hart, who was in charge of that whole thing.
Adrian Breeland was in the military.
He was a wonderful guy and coached artillery.
Math, English, history?
Well, in the curricula at that time, those were all sort of
odd items to us.
Frankly, I didn't find any stellar documentation on him.
Who was the Dean of Engineering?
Ed Gilchrist.
He was great.
He was a really wonderful man.
When it came time to call us to war, he did his best to give us time to get a degree before we were called in.
What were the normal either written or assumed rules about class and attendance and conduct in class?
Well, attendance, you were allowed
What role did the YMCA play then in student life?
the organization and or the building?
Well the organization, I can't give them credit for anything.
Because there wasn't MSC then so.
But the biggest thing is it provided the location for the
